I believe warriors aren't necessarily in great shape at the moment and some changes wouldn't hurt at all.  What I <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>don't</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> think is that this post proves conclusively that this is the case.<br>
<br>
To reiterate, I'm not saying that there <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>is</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> an equal strategic choice between tanks and hybrids.  I'm saying that this post doesn't show otherwise.  I'm also saying that I don't think the class with the best ability to absorb damage should also be the best at holding aggro.<br>
<br>
Kogar's post is interesting, I'll grant that.  I just had a minor objection to it.  I disagreed based on principle though I could have mentioned at least one conflicting experience: We use a warrior on Terris Thule.  Our tanks don't even have Ssra gear yet, we have enough trouble keeping a warrior alive, much less a Hybrid.  We don't need the aggro-on-demand for Terris herself, the warrior has all kinds of time to build aggro, but we <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>do</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> need it elsewhere in the fight.  For us, warriors are the clear choice for tanking Terris, while Hybrids are better dealing with the early adds. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A> at: 1/22/03 6:21:56 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 725<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/22/03 7:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1800.topic&index=60>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: No, there isn't any aggro control problem.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What I don't think is that this post proves conclusively that this is the case.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And what exactly would it take to prove the point to you?  You reject the arguements offered out of hand or explain them away as abberations or not reflective of a wider problem.  You've basically spent your time trying to show that in fact there is no down side to not having instant aggro control.  Yet many of us know this isn't true.  We know that having greater aggro control allows our group greater flexibility and more opportunities to do greater amounts of damage, thereby allowing everyone involved to play better, faster, easier.<br>
<br>
I mean for the love of god, why do you think we've been constantly working on obtaining better and better aggro producing weapons since we were level 1?  Because aggro control is irrelevant and our HP advantage will totally compensate for a lack of it?  You obviously completely do not understand a concept that is driven home to any Warrior worth his salt.  More aggro is inherantly better.  Less aggro is inherantly worse.  If for an experience group you have two Warriors that are identical in every way except one produces more aggro control than the other you take the one with the most aggro control.  And if you had two Warriors that were almost identical in every way except one offered a few hundred less HP but greater aggro control, you'd take the one with greater aggro control.<br>
<br>
Now, if given a situation where you have someone that is almost identical to a Warrior, has few hundred or even greater amounts less  HP, offers greater aggro control, and additional functionality in ways a Warrior will never have, you want us to believe people will take the Warrior?<br>
<br>
Sorry, you're 100% wrong.  Otherwise I would still be wielding dual lammies because my aggro control is irrelevant. <p>The Man in Black: We are men of action, lies do not become us. <br>
